data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, `ThreadAbortException`, or `Thread.ResetAbort`. It only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — all of which work identically in .NET 8. **No migration is needed.**

That said, the modern idiomatic approach would be to replace raw threads with `Task.Run` and `Parallel.ForEachAsync`, which gives you better resource utilization via the thread pool:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>
    {
        await Task.Run(() => Process(item), ct);
    });
}
```

But this is a **modernization choice**, not a required migration fix.
